<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-436-921  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 436 921.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 24 1990 v7 n38 p32(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Norton AntiVirus detects, intercepts DOS PC viruses. (SymantecCorp. to introduce Norton AntiVirus for DOS microcomputers)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sullivan, Kristina B.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Symantec Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    SYMC.andO;Product:   Norton AntiVirus (Data security software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData Security.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Norton AntiVirus Detects, Intercepts DOS PC VirusesandM;Hoping to combat the potential dangers from the 160 known data-corrupting PCviruses, Symantec Corp. will introduce The Norton AntiVirus this week.andM;The Norton AntiVirus, set to be shipped next month, is designed to detectviruses in DOS PCs by examining each file loaded from a floppy disk or anetwork file server.andP;  A 17K-byte, memory-resident &quot;virus intercept&quot; featurealso checks each application and file that is loaded into memory, said RodTurner, executive vice president of Symantec in Cupertino, Calif.andM;The Norton AntiVirus, which integrates protection, detection and eradicationin one package, can also be used to repair files damaged by viruses.andP;  Inaddition, the utility can be password-protected and customized.andM;Developed by Symantec's newly acquired Peter Norton Group, the product isdirected at companies that current have no protection against viruses.andO;American businesses lost as much as $550 million last year from unauthorizedcomputer access--which includes viruses--according to the National Center forComputer Crime Data in Los Angeles.andM;A survey conducted by Symantec of 20 Fortune 100 firms found that seven hadbeen hit by one or more viruses within the past year.andP;  One reason the threatof viruses is not well-known is because no one wants to admit that theirbusiness has been joepardized, Turner said.andM;&quot;Every knowledgeable user has ended up putting virus protection on his or hermachine,&quot; said an MIS manager at a Fortune 50 company and a beta tester ofThe Norton AntiVirus who asked not to be named.andM;The Norton AntiVirus is priced at $129.95.andP;  Protection against new viruses issupplied free through a 24-hour MS-DOS Virus Newsline and bulletin boardoperated by Symantec.andM;Symantec can be reached at (800) 343-4714.andO;</TEXT></DOC>